I don't know if this was always the plan, or what happened. I just miss my (naive) mental model of Sam as a local problem solving enthusiast and funny guy to hang out with.

It's thrown me for a huge loop this week to see what's happened under his watch. I still can't really believe the person I knew would do stuff like this. In my mind he's just another one of the nerds at Random Hall or ET or East Campus, playing magic and solving puzzles.

The whole debacle recently had me really turned inside out - my read on Sam was that he was a "fellow 2010's nerd" - member of the XKCD tribe, lover of integration bees and tricky geometry problems, physics enthusiast. The kind of person I identified as. The kind of person I am.

(I hadn't yet realized that the goatee was Not The Move; it stuck around for a cringe-inducing long time.)

Later, we met again at MIT in the math program there. Our hobbies overlapped quite a bit - Sam and I played a *lot* of Magic together, and he introduced me to League.

Many of my friends knew Sam closer than I did, but the math-science-cs-nerd-contest world in 2010 in NorCal was *very* small; most of us met through math camps and the like. Here's a nice photo of Sam and I at the Stanford Puzzle Hunt that he helped organize: https://t.co/XH4cqTuVC3

Our two schools ended up competing directly at the SLAC science bowl in 2010, which I *think* was the firs time I had met him, although if you told me that we had also met at an earlier NAQT trivia event I wouldn't be surprised.

SBF and I went to similar high schools in NorCal at the same time, and we ended up overlapping at a lot of nerdy stuff locally before meeting in college: my overwhelming impression of him before college was that he was a fellow math/CS nerd who loved puzzles and games.
